 /><strong>Repertoire</strong><br />  Beethoven: <em>Piano Trio in E-Flat 
 Major\, Op. 1 No. 1 (1795)<br /></em>L. Boulanger: <em>Deux pi├©ces en tr
 io (1917)<br /></em>R. Schumann: <em>Piano Trio No. 1 in D Minor\, Op. 63
  (1847)<br /></em><br /><strong>About the Artists</strong><br /><br />  C
 ombining the talents of three award-winning soloists\, the <strong>Weiss 
 Kaplan Stumpf Trio</strong> (WKS Trio)brings to each performance its dist
 inctive fusion of authority and experience\, energy\, and passion. The tr
 io embraces the music of the future while offering fresh insights into th
 ree centuries of masterworks. The WKS Trio has earned widespread critical
  acclaim in performances throughout the United States\, Europe\, Asia\, a
 nd the Middle East since its inception in 2001 with recital programs feat
 ured in such major venues as the Kennedy Center and Wigmore Hall and fest
 ival engagements including Changwon and Jeju Island in Korea and the Fest
 ival of the Sound in Canada. In fall 2023\, the trio released <em>The Com
 plete Beethoven Trios</em> as a 3-CD set on Bridge Records. The new album
  garnered outstanding critical response\, including reviews from the inte
 rnational <em>Gramophone Magazine</em> ("Absolute Magic")\, <em>World Mus
 ic Report</em> ("Like the legendary Beaux Arts Trio\, the Weiss Kaplan St
 umpf Trio's trademark is an uncommonly rich and full tone and the kind of
  rapt and attentive ensemble that only comes from magical empathy that th
 ey wear like a second skin from years of playing together")\, and <em>Fan
 fare Magazine</em> ("the best set since the classic set with the young Da
 nial Barenboim\, Pinchas Zukerman\, and Jacqueline du Pr├®ŌĆöthe spirit o
 f Beethoven's music comes through with profound understanding"). The WKS 
 Trio's commitment to Beethoven has also included performances of his Trip
 le Concerto in the United States and Europe\, including a Prague Festival
  appearance praised for its "rare timbral refinement\, nobility and virtu
 osic brilliance" (<em>Lidove noviny</em>\, Prague). The new Beethoven CD 
 set takes its place alongside their other recordings on Bridge Records\, 
 featuring discs with new American music as well as trios of Brahms and Sm
 etana. The latter received the enthusiastic praise of <em>Fanfare Magazin
 e</em> ("you cannot afford to be without this ŌĆ” [it] may just be the be
 st of the best Brahms B Major Trio recordings"). Devoted to new music\, t
 he trio has commissioned ensemble and concerto works for trio from distin
 guished composers Lera Auerbach\, Paul Chihara\, Michael Gilbertson\, Mic
 hael Hersch\, and Paul Lansky\, and have recorded many of these along wit
 h others by American composers Fred Lerdahl\, Chen Yi\, Clancy Newman\, a
 nd Paul Schoenfeld.<br /><br />  Laureate of the legendary Leventritt Com
 petition\, violinist <strong>Mark Kaplan</strong> is a major soloist of i
 nternational distinction\, having performed with nearly every American\, 
 European\, and Australian orchestra. His extensive discography of over 45
  commercial CDs includes concertos\, solo and chamber works from Paganini
 \, Bart├│k\, Berg\, and Sarasate\, to Schubert\, Brahms\, and Schumann. T
 o his credit are two complete recordings of Bach's solo violin works\, th
 e more recent of these on Bridge. Since 2005\, he has been violin profess
 or at the Indiana University Jacobs School of Music\, following a decade 
 as professor at UCLA. Kaplan is a graduate of The Juilliard School\, wher
 e he studied with Dorothy DeLay.<br /><br />  Cellist <strong>Peter Stump
 f</strong> is known world-wide as a soloist\, chamber musician\, and orch
 estral leader. As a soloist\, he has appeared with the Boston Symphony\, 
 Los Angeles Philharmonic\, and Philadelphia Orchestra. He has participate
 d in music festivals at Bridgehampton\, Marlboro\, Ravinia\, and Santa Fe
  and has appeared on the chamber music series at Carnegie Hall\, AliceTul
 ly Hall\, the Kennedy Center\, the Boston Celebrity Series\, the Cologne 
 Philarmonie\, the Concertgebouw\, and Casals Hall in Tokyo. He was a foun
 ding member of the Johannes String Quartet\, and his awards include first
  prize in the Washington International Competition. He was principal cell
 ist of the Los Angeles Philharmonic after serving as associate principal 
 cellist of the Philadelphia Orchestra. He has served on the faculties of 
 the New England Conservatory\, the University of Southern California\, an
 d is presently professor of cello at the Jacobs School.<br /><br />  Pian
 ist <strong>Yael Weiss</strong> has toured the United States\, Europe\, J
 apan\, and South America to great acclaim\, both in recital and as solois
 t with major orchestras. Winner of the Naumburg and Kosciuszko Foundation
  Chopin competitions\, Weiss has recorded solo works by over a dozen comp
 osers. She has served on the faculties of the Jacobs School and Universit
 y of California Santa Barbara and has given master classes worldwide. She
  is the curator and performer of 32 Bright Clouds: Beethoven Conversation
 s Around the World\, a groundbreaking global commissioning project presen
 ting piano music from countries of conflict and unrest alongside Beethove
 n's 32 piano sonatas. An advocate for the power of music in the service o
 f peace\, she is a frequent guest on national and international media. We
 iss is a graduate of the Peabody Conservatory and Mannes College\, where 
 she studied with Leon Fleisher and Richard Goode.<br /></p>
